            "body": "Hi Lizzy,\u00a0<br /><br />Thanks for your email and questions. I understand your concerns, but I don't think a summary is going to be the best option or silver bullet for the blog SEO.\u00a0<br /><br />The main reason is because Google's algorithms are very clever and now use semantics and 'conversational language analysis' to determine what your article is actually about. Simply putting a summary at the top with the keyword(s) will yield little to no results. I understand the Yoast SEO tool tells you that it should be in the first paragraph, which is more true than false, but the message is that if it doesn't feel 'natural' to be talking about your keywords there, then don't force it. We call this unnatural process 'keyword stuffing' and Google penalises for this. If you are keen to put a summary, it shouldn't be off to the side, but at the very top of the article, looking at your layout, just above the first paragraph box.<br /><br />So what can you do?<br /><br /><ul><li>You have a great amount of articles to massage. You can edit, add to and polish them so that they are easy to read and engaging. This is the number 1 ranking factor at the moment... quality content.\u00a0</li><li>Next you can work on your links. Make sure that the articles have links to other pages within the website and some off of the website. Once again, it feels right, do it, but don't force it. This shows Google that you have a holistic knowledge of your subject matter and plenty to share and expand upon.\u00a0</li><li>Inbound links, they more links you have on other websites or social pages the better (as long as they are not on spammy or paid websites). Inbound links position your site as an authority resource within its field and Google therefore will value your content over other 'like' websites.\u00a0</li></ul>These are the top 3 things that will yield\u00a0you the best results (that are within your control) at the moment. If you have\u00a0any questions, feel free to let me know.",
